1 960

Thursday 14 January 1960

At the office this morning.

1 960

Friday 15 January 1960

At the office this morning.

Was interviewed from 9:30 to 11:15 by Frank McCullough of Life Magazine on population growth in the Pacific South-West and this area in particular for a prospective series tentatively called the Continental Tilt. May have given him a few novel ideas.

Went to Dr. R.J. Prentiss' office at noon and took a retention test.

Discussed the results with him. Later Dr. Geo Fishburn called and said they agreed that everything was satisfactory and no further tests would be required. So unless something new turns up I can forget doctors until the next annual check-up.

Today received from Alan Stanton the first copy of the booklet I have had prepared showing reviews of Rattlesnakes and quotations from letters about the book. It makes a good appearance and I am well pleased with it. I have had 50 copies prepared, particularly for grandchildren.

1 960

Wednesday 3 February 1960

-----------------------------

(February 5, Continued)

Sarah Orne Jewett and Oliver Wendell Holmes to learn more about my copy of Elsie Venner which came from Sarah's library. Although Sarah's paternal grandmother was name Orne, I found no mention of James H. Orne who owned my book before Sarah.

Today Dr. Bob Spruce told me he had been an usher at the performance of Carmen on the night before the earthquake of 1906.

1 960

Thursday 4 February 1960

At the office this morning. Went to Social Security office to check on a change of rate. Found that the change will be minor and gradual as the higher contributions accumulate. Should have applied last month, but the change will be small so the loss is unimportant.

Caught the 4 PM train to Los Angeles. After dinner called Ed. Sue answered the phone and called him. His voice was quite weak at first, but strengthened. I talked to him for 15 minutes or more. He said he had been feeling bad for the past several days, had seen a doctor 2 days ago, and had had an examination including electrocardiograms. The doctor hadn't told him what was wrong; Ed seemed to think the trouble was intestinal, but from the symptoms as he described them it sounded to me like angina. I therefore decided to forgo the Stanford Conference in San Diego on the 6th and stay over to have lunch with Ed on the way back. Wrote a letter to this affect to GG.

Caught the Lark to San Francisco.

Page Edit History:
  • AmandaRobbins 03/22/2013 12:32 PM
  • BPOC 05/10/2012 01:03 PM

1 960

Friday 5 February 1960

The train arrived in San Francisco this morning an hour late, but I made it to the meeting of the directors of the State Chamber of Commerce in the French Room at the Palace Hotel in plenty of time (10 AM).

The meeting was of the usual type. After lunch we were addressed by Gerald H. Hagar of Oakland, who talked informally about a recent trip lasting a month that he and his wife had made in Russia. This was most interesting, particularly as he rambled without notes.

Leaving the meeting one of the Chamber of Commerce men told me that I was call GG. I did so and learned that Ed had died last night in his sleep. This was no surprise; I guessed what had happened. I told her to tell Allan that I would go to the Sheraton-West upon my arrival in Los Angeles next morning.

Page Edit History:
  • AmandaRobbins 03/22/2013 12:35 PM

1 960

Saturday 6 February 1960

Arrived at Los Angeles on time.

Went out to Town House and met Allan and Barney; Marg's husband. Discussed Ed's affairs, first without Barney, then went up and saw Sue and Marg. Then to Forest Lawn in Hollywood Hills (we should have gone to Forest Lawn, Glendale) and made all necessary arrangements for the funeral services.

Then went to Santa Monica, Allan, Barney, and I, and visited two possible retirement homes for Sue.

Found one that had good accommodations. On the way to the Union Station we discussed the many personal problems involved. I caught the 5:45 for [{San Diego]].

Thursday 25 August 1960

Meeting of the City Council this morning to consider a new ordinance to suppress the sale of pornography. Council Chamber packed and many standing in the halls. Miss Breed has held a seat for me; I was late because of parking difficulties. The audience was strongly in favor of the new ordinance. it was finally referred back to the City Attorney because of obvious defects. To have spoken against the ordinance would have been a mistake I think as the Library's position would have been misunderstood. Miss Breed will write the City Attorney (via the City Manager) and seek to have the ordinance so worded as to protect the Library from undesirable censorship by some of the radical proponents. I think Miss Breed may have been disappointed that we didn't speak up. But the crowd was too emotional to hope for weighing of facts or arguments.

Was at the office for a brief time before the Council meeting.

Tonight went to a dinner meeting of the Southern California Air Pollution Coordinating Council. 6:30 - 9:00. A good meeting; worthwhile reports.
